                        <scopecontent>
               <head>Scope and Contents</head>
                                 <p>This collection contains Photostats of four letters sent to and collected by Henrietta Crosby Ingersoll. Correspondence includes three letters from Horace Greeley and one letter from Senator John P. Hale.</p>
                                 <p>In his letters sent to Henrietta Ingersoll, Horace Greeley, founder and editor of the <emph render="italic">New-York Tribune</emph>, discusses various problems facing the newspaper during wartime, such as cost and subscribers. In a letter dated November 11, 1863, Greeley also voices his desire that Abraham Lincoln not be re-elected for the upcoming presidential term.</p>
                                 <p>Also included in the collection is a letter sent to Henrietta&#039;s husband, George, from Senator John P. Hale (New Hampshire). In his letter, Hale turns down George Ingersoll&#039;s request for Hale to appoint his son to West Point Military Academy.</p>
                                 <p>The original letters are located in the Mrs. H. C. Ingersoll collection in the Library of Congress.</p>
                        </scopecontent>
            


